The U.S. Congress has finally passed the Brady Bill after a long
struggle.  The bill requires a five-day waiting period before the
purchase of a handgun.  The Brady Bill, the recent ban on the purchase
of assault weapons, and other pending bills are being viewed by some
anti-gun proponents as an indication that the tide has turned in favor
of gun control.

Opponents of gun control, led by the National Rifle Association and
citing their authority as the Second Amendment to the Constitution,
continue their opposition to all forms of gun control.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d27"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA021090-0005"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E">   

There appears to be a trend in the U.S. toward the implementation of
gun controls.  A recent media report indicates that 87 percent of gun
owners themselves favor a seven-day waiting period for handguns; three
quarters favor registration of semi-automatic weapons and half favor
registration of rifles and shotguns.

The Second Amendment to the Constitution, however, continues to be the
thorn in the side of any legal effort toward gun control.  Pro-gun
advocates accept the wording of the amendment at face value, that is,
a right to bear arms.  Gun control advocates attempt to put the
amendment in its 1792 context in defining its meaning.</SUM>

